<DocsLayout title="Docker & Experiments" toc={toc}>

  <h1>Docker & Experiments</h1>

  <p>
    Docker is mandatory for all experiments on AIRLab servers. It is not optional, and
    it is not just for production code. Running experiments inside containers ensures
    that every result is reproducible — by you six months from now, by your co-supervisor,
    and by any future lab member who builds on your work.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Why Docker ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="why">Why Docker?</h2>

  <p>
    Without containers, every researcher installs packages globally with <code>pip</code>
    or <code>conda</code>. Over time, incompatible versions accumulate, experiments break,
    and nobody can tell which version of a library produced which result. Docker fixes this:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Isolation</strong> — your dependencies cannot interfere with anyone else's, and vice versa.</li>
    <li><strong>Reproducibility</strong> — pin every dependency to an exact version; anyone can rebuild the same environment from scratch.</li>
    <li><strong>Portability</strong> — the same container runs on Westworld, a cloud VM, or your laptop (CPU-only).</li>
    <li><strong>Clean servers</strong> — no global package pollution; the server OS stays pristine.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>The standard development cycle is:</p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Write</strong> a <code>Dockerfile</code> describing your environment</li>
    <li><strong>Build</strong> it into a Docker image (a binary snapshot)</li>
    <li><strong>Run</strong> the image as a container, mounting your code and dataset from outside</li>
    <li><strong>Develop / debug</strong> by attaching to the running container</li>
    <li><strong>Stop and remove</strong> the container when done; the image can be rebuilt at any time</li>
  </ol>

  <!-- ── Project Structure ──────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="structure">Project Structure</h2>

  <p>
    Every project should follow this layout. It makes your repository self-contained —
    anyone who clones it can build the environment and run the code without asking you
    anything.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="text"
    filename="my_project/"
    code={`my_project/
├── src/                   # your source code
│   ├── train.py
│   ├── evaluate.py
│   └── models/
├── configs/               # YAML/JSON configuration files
│   └── default.yaml
├── docker/
│   ├── Dockerfile
│   └── build.sh           # convenience build script
├── requirements.txt       # Python dependencies (pinned versions)
├── run.sh                 # convenience run script (wraps docker run)
├── .gitignore
└── README.md              # setup & usage instructions`}
  />

  <p>
    Keep a <code>build.sh</code> and a <code>run.sh</code> in the repo so every
    collaborator uses the exact same flags — no more "it worked on my machine" because
    someone forgot a mount or an environment variable.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Dockerfile ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="dockerfile">Writing a Dockerfile</h2>

  <p>
    Start from an official NVIDIA base image that bundles CUDA and cuDNN. Pick the
    version that matches the CUDA toolkit installed on Westworld (ask your co-supervisor
    or run <code>nvidia-smi</code> and check the top-right CUDA version).
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="dockerfile"
    filename="docker/Dockerfile"
    code={`# ── Base image ────────────────────────────────────────────
# Browse available tags at: https://hub.docker.com/r/nvidia/cuda/tags
FROM nvidia/cuda:12.1.0-cudnn8-runtime-ubuntu22.04

# ── System dependencies ───────────────────────────────────
RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends \
      python3.11 \
      python3.11-venv \
      python3-pip \
      git \
      libgl1 \
      libglib2.0-0 \
    && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*

# ── Python environment ────────────────────────────────────
WORKDIR /workspace
COPY requirements.txt .

RUN pip install --no-cache-dir --upgrade pip \
    && pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt

# ── Project code ──────────────────────────────────────────
COPY src/ ./src/
COPY configs/ ./configs/

# Default command (override at runtime)
CMD ["python3", "src/train.py"]`}
  />

  <p>
    Pin every dependency to an exact version in <code>requirements.txt</code>:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="text"
    filename="requirements.txt"
    code={`torch==2.2.1+cu121
torchvision==0.17.1+cu121
torchaudio==2.2.1+cu121
--extra-index-url https://download.pytorch.org/whl/cu121

numpy==1.26.4
opencv-python-headless==4.9.0.80
matplotlib==3.8.4
tqdm==4.66.2
pyyaml==6.0.1
tensorboard==2.16.2`}
  />

  <!-- ── Building ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="building">Building Images</h2>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="westworld — project root"
    code={`# Build the image. Convention: <username>/<project>:<version>
docker build --rm -t lastname/my_project:v1 -f docker/Dockerfile .

# Verify the image was built
docker images | grep my_project

# Remove dangling images (untagged build cache)
docker image prune`}
  />

  <p>
    The <code>--rm</code> flag removes intermediate containers after the build, keeping the
    server tidy. Rebuild whenever you change <code>Dockerfile</code> or
    <code>requirements.txt</code>.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Running ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="running">Running Containers</h2>

  <p>
    AIRLab servers provide a helper script called <code>run-docker</code> that wraps
    <code>docker run</code> with sensible defaults (GPU assignment, directory mounts,
    user permissions). Ask your co-supervisor how to obtain it.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="westworld"
    code={`# Usage: run-docker <gpu_indices> <cpu_cores> <command...>
# Example: GPU 0, 4 CPU cores, run training
run-docker 0 4 python3 src/train.py --config configs/default.yaml

# Two GPUs (0 and 1), 8 cores
run-docker 0,1 8 python3 src/train_multi_gpu.py

# Interactive bash shell for debugging
run-docker 0 4 bash`}
  />

  <p>
    If <code>run-docker</code> is not yet available, here is the equivalent raw Docker
    command with all flags explained:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="westworld"
    code={`# Get your UID and GID (needed to avoid root-owned output files)
id lastname
# example output: uid=1085(lastname) gid=20002(users) ...

docker run \\
  -d \\                                           # run in background (detached)
  --rm \\                                         # auto-remove container when it exits
  -it \\                                          # allocate a pseudo-TTY
  --gpus '"device=7"' \\                          # assign GPU 7
  --cpuset-cpus 104-111 \\                        # assign CPU cores 104–111
  -u 1085:20002 \\                                # run as your user (uid:gid)
  -e HOST_UID=1085 -e HOST_GID=20002 \\          # pass uid/gid as env vars
  -w /workspace \\                               # set working directory inside container
  --mount type=bind,source=/home/lastname/storage/project,target=/workspace \\
  --mount type=bind,source=/home/lastname/dataset/private,target=/workspace/datasets \\
  --name lastname_my_project \\                   # name the container
  lastname/my_project:v1 \\                       # image to use
  python3 src/train.py`}
  />

  <p>
    Key flags to remember:
  </p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Flag</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>-d</code></td><td>Detach — container runs in background</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>--rm</code></td><td>Remove container automatically when it stops</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>-it</code></td><td>Keep a terminal attached (needed for interactive use)</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>--gpus</code></td><td>Assign specific GPUs (must match booked resources)</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>--cpuset-cpus</code></td><td>Restrict to specific CPU cores</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>-u uid:gid</code></td><td>Run as your user so output files are owned by you</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>--mount</code></td><td>Bind-mount a host directory into the container</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>--name</code></td><td>Give the container a recognisable name</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="westworld"
    code={`# Useful container management commands
docker ps                           # list running containers
docker ps | grep lastname           # filter to yours
docker exec -it CONTAINER_ID bash   # attach a shell to a running container
docker logs CONTAINER_ID            # view container output
docker stop CONTAINER_ID            # stop a running container
docker rm   CONTAINER_ID            # remove a stopped container
docker rmi  lastname/my_project:v1  # delete an image`}
  />

  <!-- ── Run Configs ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="runconfigs">Run Configurations (.runconfig)</h2>

  <p>
    The <code>.runconfig</code> file lets you declare persistent options for
    <code>run-docker</code> without repeating them on the command line every time.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename=".runconfig"
    code={`# Mount your private dataset directory into the container (read-only)
-v ~/dataset/private/coco:/data/coco:ro

# Mount a shared lab dataset (read-only)
-v /data/shared/imagenet:/data/imagenet:ro

# Expose a port (e.g., for TensorBoard)
-p 6006:6006

# Set environment variables
-e WANDB_API_KEY=your_key_here
-e PYTHONPATH=/workspace/src`}
  />

  <!-- ── VS Code Integration ────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="vscode">VS Code Integration</h2>

  <p>
    The recommended workflow is to run your container in the background and attach VS Code
    directly to it. This gives you a full IDE (IntelliSense, debugging, notebooks) inside
    the container environment, without any manual port management.
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>
      Install the <strong>Dev Containers</strong> extension in VS Code
      (<code>ms-vscode-remote.remote-containers</code>)
    </li>
    <li>
      Start your container with <code>-d -it</code> (detached + pseudo-TTY) so it stays
      alive waiting for a connection
    </li>
    <li>
      Open the VS Code Command Palette (<kbd>Ctrl+Shift+P</kbd>) →
      <em>Dev Containers: Attach to Running Container</em> → select your container
    </li>
    <li>
      Your project folder (<code>/workspace</code>) opens in a full remote VS Code session
      running inside the container
    </li>
  </ol>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <svg class="w-5 h-5 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5 text-accent-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor"
         stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
      <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/><line x1="12" y1="8" x2="12" y2="12"/>
      <line x1="12" y1="16" x2="12.01" y2="16"/>
    </svg>
    <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
      The <strong>Remote - SSH</strong> extension and the <strong>Dev Containers</strong>
      extension can be used together: SSH into the server first, then attach to a container
      running on that server. VS Code handles the tunnel transparently.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h3>Port forwarding</h3>

  <p>
    When a process inside the container listens on a port (e.g., TensorBoard on 6006,
    Jupyter on 8888), VS Code can forward it to your local machine automatically.
    Open the <strong>Ports</strong> panel (<kbd>Alt+J</kbd> → Ports tab) and click
    <em>Add Port</em> if the auto-detection misses it.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Jupyter ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="jupyter">Jupyter Notebooks</h2>

  <p>
    Notebooks are useful for exploration and visualisation, but should not contain core
    training logic. To run Jupyter inside a container:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="westworld"
    code={`run-docker 0 4 jupyter notebook --ip=0.0.0.0 --port=8888 --no-browser`}
  />

  <p>
    Then forward the port on your local machine to access it in the browser:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="local machine"
    code={`# Forward remote port 8888 to local 8888
ssh -L 8888:localhost:8888 ww

# Open in browser: http://localhost:8888
# (copy the token from the Jupyter output on the server)`}
  />

  <p>
    If you are attached via VS Code (see <a href="#vscode">VS Code Integration</a> above),
    VS Code will detect the Jupyter port and offer to forward it automatically. You can
    also run <code>.ipynb</code> notebooks directly in the VS Code editor using the
    <strong>Jupyter</strong> extension (<code>@tag:notebookKernelJupyterNotebook</code>),
    selecting the container's Python interpreter as the kernel.
  </p>

  <!-- ── TensorBoard ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="tensorboard">TensorBoard</h2>

  <p>
    TensorBoard is the standard tool for tracking and comparing experiments.
    It can visualise scalars (loss, accuracy), images, model graphs, and embeddings.
  </p>

  <h3>Logging from PyTorch</h3>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="python"
    filename="src/train.py"
    code={`from torch.utils.tensorboard import SummaryWriter

# Create a writer with a descriptive run name
writer = SummaryWriter(log_dir="runs/exp_lr1e-3_bs32")

for epoch in range(num_epochs):
    # Log scalars
    writer.add_scalar("Loss/train", train_loss, epoch)
    writer.add_scalar("Loss/val",   val_loss,   epoch)
    writer.add_scalar("Accuracy",   accuracy,   epoch)

writer.close()`}
  />

  <h3>Launching TensorBoard</h3>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="westworld (inside the container)"
    code={`# Point TensorBoard at your runs directory
tensorboard --logdir runs/ --port 6006

# Or compare multiple experiments at once
tensorboard --logdir_spec exp1:runs/exp_lr1e-3,exp2:runs/exp_lr1e-4 --port 6006`}
  />

  <p>
    Then forward port 6006 from the server to your local machine — VS Code does this
    automatically when TensorBoard starts, or you can do it manually:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="local machine"
    code={`ssh -L 6006:localhost:6006 ww
# Open in browser: http://localhost:6006`}
  />

  <h3>Projector (embedding visualisation)</h3>

  <p>
    TensorBoard's Projector tab lets you project high-dimensional embeddings into 2D/3D
    space using PCA, UMAP, or t-SNE. This is extremely useful for understanding whether
    your model's latent space is well-structured — for example, whether embeddings of the
    same class cluster together, or to spot outliers.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="python"
    code={`# Log embeddings with optional metadata (labels, images)
writer.add_embedding(
    features,           # Tensor of shape (N, D)
    metadata=labels,    # list of N label strings
    label_img=images,   # Tensor of shape (N, C, H, W) — optional
    global_step=epoch,
    tag="embeddings"
)`}
  />

  <!-- ── Best Practices ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="best-practices">Best Practices</h2>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Do</th><th>Don't</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Pin all dependency versions in <code>requirements.txt</code></td>
        <td>Use <code>pip install torch</code> with no version pin</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Use <code>--no-cache-dir</code> in <code>pip install</code></td>
        <td>Let pip cache accumulate inside image layers</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Chain <code>RUN</code> commands with <code>&amp;&amp;</code> to reduce layers</td>
        <td>Create a separate <code>RUN</code> for each <code>apt-get install</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Tag images with meaningful version strings (<code>:v2</code>, <code>:exp-aug24</code>)</td>
        <td>Always use <code>:latest</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Mount datasets from outside the container (<code>-v</code> or <code>--mount</code>)</td>
        <td>Copy large datasets into the image with <code>COPY</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Use config files for experiment variants — keep source code unchanged</td>
        <td>Hardcode hyperparameters inside <code>train.py</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Log to files and TensorBoard rather than printing to the console</td>
        <td>Rely on <code>print()</code> as your only record of experiment results</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Run <code>docker image prune</code> periodically</td>
        <td>Let stale images accumulate and fill the server disk</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

